# 🥈 Second Largest Element in an Array

<p align="center">
Find the <b>second largest element</b> in a given array.
</p>

---

## 📌 Problem Statement

Given an array of integers, return the **second largest element** present in the array.

### Example

```
Input:  [3, 7, 2, 9, 5]
Output: 7
```

Explanation:

```
Sorted array → [2,3,5,7,9]

Largest        = 9
Second Largest = 7
```

---

# 🚀 Approaches

We can solve this problem using **three different approaches**.

| Approach | Idea | Time Complexity |
|--------|------|----------------|
| Brute Force | Sort the array | O(n log n) |
| Better | Two traversals | O(n) |
| Optimal | Single traversal | O(n) |

---

# 1️⃣ Brute Force Approach (Sorting)

### 💡 Idea

1. Sort the array.
2. The last element is the largest.
3. Traverse backward to find the first element **not equal to largest**.

### 🧠 Visualization

```
Array: [3,7,2,9,5]

After Sorting
[2,3,5,7,9]

Largest = 9
Second Largest = 7
```

### 💻 Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int secondLargest(vector<int>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size();

    sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());

    for(int i = n-2; i >= 0; i--) {
        if(arr[i] != arr[n-1]) {
            return arr[i];
        }
    }

    return -1;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {3,7,2,9,5};
    cout << secondLargest(arr);
}
```

### ⏱ Complexity

```
Time Complexity  : O(n log n)
Space Complexity : O(1)
```

---

# 2️⃣ Better Approach (Two Traversals)

### 💡 Idea

Step 1 → Find the **largest element**

Step 2 → Traverse again and find the **largest element smaller than the largest**

### 🧠 Visualization

```
Array: [3,7,2,9,5]

Largest = 9

Second pass:
3 → candidate
7 → candidate
2 → ignore
5 → candidate

Second Largest = 7
```

### 💻 Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int secondLargest(vector<int>& arr) {

    int largest = arr[0];

    for(int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
        if(arr[i] > largest) {
            largest = arr[i];
        }
    }

    int secondLargest = -1;

    for(int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
        if(arr[i] != largest && arr[i] > secondLargest) {
            secondLargest = arr[i];
        }
    }

    return secondLargest;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {3,7,2,9,5};
    cout << secondLargest(arr);
}
```

### ⏱ Complexity

```
Time Complexity  : O(n)
Space Complexity : O(1)
```

---

# 3️⃣ Optimal Approach (Single Traversal)

### 💡 Idea

Maintain two variables:

```
largest
secondLargest
```

Update them while traversing the array once.

### 🧠 Visualization

```
Array: [3,7,2,9,5]

Start
largest = 3
secondLargest = -1

7 > 3
largest = 7
secondLargest = 3

2 < 7 → ignore

9 > 7
largest = 9
secondLargest = 7

5 < 9 but < 7 → ignore

Final Answer → 7
```

### 💻 Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int secondLargest(vector<int>& arr) {

    int largest = arr[0];
    int secondLargest = -1;

    for(int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {

        if(arr[i] > largest) {
            secondLargest = largest;
            largest = arr[i];
        }

        else if(arr[i] < largest && arr[i] > secondLargest) {
            secondLargest = arr[i];
        }
    }

    return secondLargest;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {3,7,2,9,5};
    cout << secondLargest(arr);
}
```

### ⏱ Complexity

```
Time Complexity  : O(n)
Space Complexity : O(1)
```

---

# ⭐ Conclusion

| Method | Time Complexity | Recommended |
|------|----------------|-------------|
| Sorting | O(n log n) | ❌ |
| Two Traversals | O(n) | 👍 |
| Single Traversal | O(n) | ⭐ Best |

The **optimal approach using a single traversal** is the most efficient solution.

